                <td>Title, author, date, genre</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real Knowledge Graph examples</h2>
        <p>Two patterns show how brands get recognized and what changes as a result.</p>

        <h3>Example 1: Local restaurant chain</h3>
        <p>A 5-location restaurant implements <code>Organization</code> and <code>LocalBusiness</code> schema on every location page, maintains consistent NAP data across 60+ directories, and earns Wikipedia coverage through local press. Within 6 months, searching the restaurant name shows a knowledge panel with operating hours, location links, aggregate ratings, and a description pulled from Wikidata.</p>

        <h3>Example 2: B2B SaaS brand</h3>
        <p>A project management tool publishes 30+ in-depth articles monthly, earns citations in industry publications like TechCrunch and G2, adds <code>Organization</code> schema with <code>sameAs</code> links to their Wikipedia and Wikidata pages. Over 12 months, Google begins associating the brand name with the "project management software" entity class — appearing in AI Overviews for category queries even without ranking #1 organically.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Knowledge Graph vs. knowledge panel — what's the difference?</h2>
        <p>These terms are often used interchangeably, but they describe different things.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Knowledge Graph</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Google's internal database (not visible)</li>
              <li>Stores entity facts and relationships</li>
              <li>500B+ facts, 5B+ entities</li>
              <li>Built from Wikipedia, web crawl, schema</li>
              <li>Powers all entity-aware Google features</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Knowledge Panel</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>The visible UI element in Google search</li>
              <li>Displays facts pulled from the Knowledge Graph</li>
              <li>Appears right side (desktop) or top (mobile)</li>
              <li>Can be claimed and partially edited by brands</li>
              <li>One output of Knowledge Graph recognition</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 steps to get your brand into the Knowledge Graph</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Verify your Google Business Profile.</strong> GBP verification is the fastest route to entity recognition for local businesses. Google's own product feeds entity data directly into the Knowledge Graph.</li>
          <li><strong>Add Organization schema to your homepage.</strong> Use JSON-LD with <code>@type: Organization</code>, your legal name, URL, logo, founding date, and <code>sameAs</code> links to Wikipedia and Wikidata.</li>
          <li><strong>Create or improve your Wikipedia page.</strong> Wikipedia is Google's single most trusted structured data source. If you don't qualify yet, Wikidata is more accessible and contributes to the Knowledge Graph directly.</li>
          <li><strong>Ensure consistent NAP across 50+ directories.</strong> Name-Address-Phone consistency is how Google confirms your entity is real. Inconsistencies create entity confusion and slow down Knowledge Graph recognition.</li>
          <li><strong>Earn mentions on authoritative sources.</strong> Crunchbase, LinkedIn company page, industry publications, and government databases all contribute to entity authority. Each mention that includes your brand name + URL is a signal.</li>
          <li><strong>Use sameAs markup.</strong> The <code>sameAs</code> property in your Organization schema should link to every authoritative profile: Wikipedia, Wikidata, LinkedIn, Twitter/X, Crunchbase. This is how Google connects distributed entity data.</li>
          <li><strong>Publish a consistent author entity.</strong> For content-heavy brands, establishing Person schema for key authors (with <code>sameAs</code> to LinkedIn and Wikipedia) builds topical authority that feeds back into the brand's Knowledge Graph record.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — inconsistent entity names</div>
          <p>If your GBP says "Acme Corp," your website says "Acme Corporation," your LinkedIn says "Acme," and your Wikipedia page says "Acme Corp. Ltd," Google sees four different entities, not one. Pick the canonical form of your name and enforce it everywhere before doing anything else.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common Knowledge Graph mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Skipping schema markup.</strong> Without Organization JSON-LD, Google has to infer your entity from unstructured text — slower and less reliable.</li>
          <li><strong>Missing sameAs links.</strong> Without them, Google can't confirm your website is the same entity as your Wikipedia page, GBP, and LinkedIn profile.</li>
          <li><strong>Name inconsistency across platforms.</strong> Every variation fragments your entity signals. One canonical name, everywhere.</li>
          <li><strong>Treating Wikipedia as optional.</strong> Wikipedia is not required, but it is the highest-weight single source Google trusts. If your brand qualifies for a Wikipedia page, not having one is a missed opportunity.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring Wikidata.</strong> Wikidata is directly consumed by the Knowledge Graph and is much easier to create than Wikipedia. A complete Wikidata entry with correct properties can accelerate entity recognition significantly.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
